ldfish And Clowns\" [Radio Edit] / \"The Perception Of Johnny Punter\" [US Radio Edit]\n* 1999: \"Incomplete\" (feat. [[Elisabeth Troy|Elisabeth Antwi]]) / \"Wake Up Call\" [Acoustic Version] / \"Incomplete\" [Demo Version Recorded At The Castle Marouatte France]\n* 2008: \"Arc Of The Curve\" [Single Edit] / \"Arc of the Curve\"\n* 2008: \"Zoe 25\" [Radio Edit] / \"Dark Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008] / \"13th Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008]\n* 2014: \"[[Blind to the Beautiful]]\"\n\n===EPs===\n* 2018: \"A Parley with Angels\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Fish (singer)}}\n*Official website (as of 2017) \u2013 {{Site|http://fishmusic.scot}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fish-thecompany.com/}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fishheads.club/}}\n*{{IMDb name|name=Fish|id=0279258}} provides information on Fish and his acting career.\n\n{{Fish (singer)}}\n{{Marillion}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fish}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:Art rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marillion members]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dalkeith High School]]\n[[Category:People from Dalkeith]]\n[[Category:People from Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Scottish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish socialists]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActing:Punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Cursing the fig tree", "text_new": "{{Gospel Jesus}}\nThe '''cursing of the fig tree''' is an incident in the [[gospels]], presented in [[gospel of Mark|Mark]] and [[gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] as a miracle in connection with the entry into Jerusalem.{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=67}} [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] presents it as a parable, and the gospel of [[John|John]] omits the curse entirely and shifts the incident with which it is connected, the cleansing of the temple, to the beginning of Jesus' career.{{sfn|Edwards|2002|p=338}} Its image is taken from the Old Testament symbol of the fig tree representing Israel, and its message is that Israel has failed and will be destroyed, just as the fig tree withers and dies,{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=67}}{{sfn|Kinman|1995|p=123}} although Luke shifts the focus from the temple and its leadership to those within Israel who might still hear Jesus and reorder their lives in readiness for the coming Kingdom of.\n\n==Commentary==\n[[File:Miracleofthefig.jpg|150px|thumb|Byzantine [[icon]] of the cursing of the fig tree.]]\nMost scholars believe that [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]] was the first gospel and was used as a source by the authors of Matthew and Luke.{{sfn|Burkett|2002|p=143}} In the Jewish scriptures the people of Israel are sometimes represented as figs on a fig tree ([[Hosea 9]]:10, [[Jeremiah 24]]), or a fig tree that bears no fruit ([[Jeremiah 8]]:13), and in [[Micah 4]]:4 the age of the [[messiah]] is pictured as one in which each man would sit under his fig tree without fear; the cursing of the fig tree in Mark and Matthew and the parallel story in Luke are thus symbolically directed against the Jews, who have not accepted Jesus as king.{{sfn|Burkett|2002|p=170-171}}{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=175}} At first sight the destruction of the fig tree does not seem to fit Jesus' behaviour elsewhere, but the miracle stories are directed against property rather than people, and form a \"prophetic act of judgement\".{{sfn|Keener|1999|p=503-504}} [[Bertrand Russell]] in ''[[Why I Am Not a Christian]]'' (one of the most influential books of the 20th century,<ref>https://www.nypl.org/voices/print-publications/books-of-the-century</ref>) used the tale to cast a shade on the greatness of Jesus, and New Testament scholar [[Thomas Walter Manson]] noted it as \"a tale of miraculous power wasted in the service of an ill temper\".<ref>''Jesus Behaving Badly: The Puzzling Paradoxes of the Man from Galilee'',  Mark L. Strauss, [https://books.google.com/books?id=A-2OBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jesus+Behaving+Badly:+The+Puzzling+Paradoxes+of+the+Man+from+Galilee%27&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjC4cnzk__nAhXSqZ4KHfPcDvcQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=snippet&q=Bertrand&f=false p. 64].</ref>\n\n===Gospel of Matthew, 21:18-22===\nMatthew compresses Mark's divided account into a single story.{{sfn|Keener|1999|p=503}} Here the fig tree withers immediately the curse is pronounced, driving the narrative forward to Jesus' encounter with the Jewish priesthood and his curse against them and the temple.{{sfn|Perkins|2009|p=166-167}} Jesus responds to the disciples' expressions of wonder with a brief discourse on faith and prayer, and while this makes it less clear that the dead fig tree is related to the fate of the temple, in Matthew 24:32-35 the author follows Mark closely in presenting the \"lesson\" (in Greek, ''parabole'') of the budding tree as a sign of the certain coming of the Son of Man.{{sfn|Kinman|1995|p=124}}{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=74-75}}\n\n===Gospel of Luke, 13:6-9===\nLuke replaces the miracle with a parable, probably originating from the same body of tradition that lies behind Mark.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=126}} Jesus and the disciples are travelling to Jerusalem when they hear of the deaths of Galileans, and Jesus gives the events a prophetic interpretation through a parable: a man planted a fig tree expecting it to bear fruit, but despite his visits it remained barren; the owner's patience wore thin, but the gardener pleaded for a little more time; the owner agrees, but the question of whether the tree would bear fruit, i.e. acts that manifest the Kingdom of God, is left hanging.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=127}} Luke has Jesus end his story with a warning that if the followers do not repent they will perish.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=126}}\n\n==Parallels in other texts==\n\nA very different story appears in [[Infancy Gospel of Thomas]], but has a similar quotation from Jesus: \"\u2026behold, now also thou shalt be withered like a tree, and shalt not bear leaves, neither root, nor fruit.\" (III:2).<ref>James, M. R., 1924, ''The Apocryphal New Testament'', Oxford: Clarendon Press</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Fig tree cursed|Cursing the fig tree}}\n* [[Figs in the Bible]]\n* [[Life of Jesus in the New Testament]]\n* [[Parable of the budding fig tree]]\n* [[Parable of the barren fig tree]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Burkett\n| first1           = Delbert Royce\n| title            = An introduction to the New Testament and the origins of Christianity\n| publisher        = Cambridge University Press\n| year             = 2002\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=EcsQknxV-xQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=An+introduction+to+the+New+Testament+and+the+origins+of+Christianity+Delbert+Royce+Burkett#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780521007207\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Carroll\n| first1           = John T.\n| title            = Luke: A Commentary\n| publisher        = Westminster John Knox Press\n| year             = 2012\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=krRY23eR55IC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780664221065\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Cousland\n| first1           = J.R.C.\n| title            = Holy Terror: Jesus in the Infancy Gospel of Thomas\n| publisher        = Bloomsbury Publishing\n| year             = 2017\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=rsw6DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780567668189\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Dumbrell\n| first1           = W.J.\n| title            = The Search for Order: Biblical Eschatology in Focus\n| publisher        = Wipf and Stock\n| year             = 2001\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=irNKAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9781579107963\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Edwards\n| first1           = James R.\n| title            = The Gospel According to Mark\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 2002\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=0MjWS_4La_EC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780851117782\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Getty-Sullivan\n| first1           = Mary Ann \n| title            = Parables of the Kingdom: Jesus and the Use of Parables in the Synoptic Tradition\n| publisher        = Liturgical Press\n| year             = 2007\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=zt3vK-hJzQYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780814629932\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Keener\n| first1           = Craig\n| title            = A Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 1999\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=sWzhEdBZOp4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=A+Commentary+on+the+Gospel+of+Matthew#v=onepage&q=fig%20tree&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780802838216\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Kinman\n| first1           = Brent\n| title            = Jesus' entry into Jerusalem: in the context of Lukan theology and the politics of his day\n| publisher        = Brill\n| year             = 1995\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=pRdiwjAeYLkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jesus%27+entry+into+Jerusalem:+in+the+context+of+Lukan+theology+and+the+politics+of+his+day#v=onepage&q=Jesus'%20entry%20into%20Jerusalem%3A%20in%20the%20context%20of%20Lukan%20theology%20and%20the%20politics%20of%20his%20day&f=false\n| isbn             = 9004103309\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Perkins\n| first1           = Pheme \n| title            = Introduction to the Synoptic Gospels\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 2009\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=lMUZhdgmOR8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Pheme+Perkins%22#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780802865533\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Reddish\n| first1           = Mitchell G.\n| title            = An Introduction to The Gospels\n| publisher        = Abingdon Press\n| year             = 2011\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=hliGUOv18cQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9781426750083\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n\n{{Jesus footer}}\n{{Miracles of Jesus|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Curses]]\n[[Category:Miracles of Jesus]]\n[[Category:Ficus| ]]\n[[Category:Trees in Christianity]]\n", "text_old": "{{Gospel Jesus}}\nThe '''cursing of the fig tree''' is an incident in the [[gospels]], presented in [[gospel of Mark|Mark]] and [[gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] as a miracle in connection with the entry into Jerusalem.{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=67}} [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] presents it as a parable, and the gospel of [[John|John]] omits the curse entirely and shifts the incident with which it is connected, the cleansing of the temple, to the beginning of Jesus' career.{{sfn|Edwards|2002|p=338}} Its image is taken from the Old Testament symbol of the fig tree representing Israel, and its message is that Israel has failed and will be destroyed, just as the fig tree withers and dies,{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=67}}{{sfn|Kinman|1995|p=123}} although Luke shifts the focus from the temple and its leadership to those within Israel who might still hear Jesus and reorder their lives in readiness for the coming Kingdom of God.{{sfn|Carroll|2012|p=280}}\n\n==Commentary==\n[[File:Miracleofthefig.jpg|150px|thumb|Byzantine [[icon]] of the cursing of the fig tree.]]\nMost scholars believe that [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]] was the first gospel and was used as a source by the authors of Matthew and Luke.{{sfn|Burkett|2002|p=143}} In the Jewish scriptures the people of Israel are sometimes represented as figs on a fig tree ([[Hosea 9]]:10, [[Jeremiah 24]]), or a fig tree that bears no fruit ([[Jeremiah 8]]:13), and in [[Micah 4]]:4 the age of the [[messiah]] is pictured as one in which each man would sit under his fig tree without fear; the cursing of the fig tree in Mark and Matthew and the parallel story in Luke are thus symbolically directed against the Jews, who have not accepted Jesus as king.{{sfn|Burkett|2002|p=170-171}}{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=175}} At first sight the destruction of the fig tree does not seem to fit Jesus' behaviour elsewhere, but the miracle stories are directed against property rather than people, and form a \"prophetic act of judgement\".{{sfn|Keener|1999|p=503-504}} [[Bertrand Russell]] in ''[[Why I Am Not a Christian]]'' (one of the most influential books of the 20th century,<ref>https://www.nypl.org/voices/print-publications/books-of-the-century</ref>) used the tale to cast a shade on the greatness of Jesus, and New Testament scholar [[Thomas Walter Manson]] noted it as \"a tale of miraculous power wasted in the service of an ill temper\".<ref>''Jesus Behaving Badly: The Puzzling Paradoxes of the Man from Galilee'',  Mark L. Strauss, [https://books.google.com/books?id=A-2OBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jesus+Behaving+Badly:+The+Puzzling+Paradoxes+of+the+Man+from+Galilee%27&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjC4cnzk__nAhXSqZ4KHfPcDvcQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=snippet&q=Bertrand&f=false p. 64].</ref>\n\n===Gospel of Mark, 11:12-25===\nMark uses the cursing of the barren fig tree to bracket and comment on his story of the Jewish temple: Jesus and his disciples are on their way to Jerusalem when Jesus curses a fig tree because it bears no fruit; in Jerusalem he drives the money-changers from the temple; and the next morning the disciples find that the fig tree has withered and died, with the implied message that the temple is cursed and will wither because, like the fig tree, it failed to produce the fruit of righteousness.{{sfn|Reddish|2011|p=79-80}} The episode concludes with a discourse on the power of prayer, leading some scholars to interpret this, rather than the eschatological aspect, as its primary motif,{{sfn|Kinman|1995|p=123-124}} but at verse 28 Mark has Jesus again use the image of the fig tree to make plain that Jerusalem will fall and the Jewish nation be brought to an end before their generation passes away.{{sfn|Dumbrell|2001|p=202}}\n\n===Gospel of Matthew, 21:18-22===\nMatthew compresses Mark's divided account into a single story.{{sfn|Keener|1999|p=503}} Here the fig tree withers immediately the curse is pronounced, driving the narrative forward to Jesus' encounter with the Jewish priesthood and his curse against them and the temple.{{sfn|Perkins|2009|p=166-167}} Jesus responds to the disciples' expressions of wonder with a brief discourse on faith and prayer, and while this makes it less clear that the dead fig tree is related to the fate of the temple, in Matthew 24:32-35 the author follows Mark closely in presenting the \"lesson\" (in Greek, ''parabole'') of the budding tree as a sign of the certain coming of the Son of Man.{{sfn|Kinman|1995|p=124}}{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=74-75}}\n\n===Gospel of Luke, 13:6-9===\nLuke replaces the miracle with a parable, probably originating from the same body of tradition that lies behind Mark.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=126}} Jesus and the disciples are travelling to Jerusalem when they hear of the deaths of Galileans, and Jesus gives the events a prophetic interpretation through a parable: a man planted a fig tree expecting it to bear fruit, but despite his visits it remained barren; the owner's patience wore thin, but the gardener pleaded for a little more time; the owner agrees, but the question of whether the tree would bear fruit, i.e. acts that manifest the Kingdom of God, is left hanging.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=127}} Luke has Jesus end his story with a warning that if the followers do not repent they will perish.{{sfn|Getty-Sullivan|2007|p=126}}\n\n==Parallels in other texts==\n\nA very different story appears in [[Infancy Gospel of Thomas]], but has a similar quotation from Jesus: \"\u2026behold, now also thou shalt be withered like a tree, and shalt not bear leaves, neither root, nor fruit.\" (III:2).<ref>James, M. R., 1924, ''The Apocryphal New Testament'', Oxford: Clarendon Press</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Fig tree cursed|Cursing the fig tree}}\n* [[Figs in the Bible]]\n* [[Life of Jesus in the New Testament]]\n* [[Parable of the budding fig tree]]\n* [[Parable of the barren fig tree]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Burkett\n| first1           = Delbert Royce\n| title            = An introduction to the New Testament and the origins of Christianity\n| publisher        = Cambridge University Press\n| year             = 2002\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=EcsQknxV-xQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=An+introduction+to+the+New+Testament+and+the+origins+of+Christianity+Delbert+Royce+Burkett#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780521007207\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Carroll\n| first1           = John T.\n| title            = Luke: A Commentary\n| publisher        = Westminster John Knox Press\n| year             = 2012\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=krRY23eR55IC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780664221065\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Cousland\n| first1           = J.R.C.\n| title            = Holy Terror: Jesus in the Infancy Gospel of Thomas\n| publisher        = Bloomsbury Publishing\n| year             = 2017\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=rsw6DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780567668189\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Dumbrell\n| first1           = W.J.\n| title            = The Search for Order: Biblical Eschatology in Focus\n| publisher        = Wipf and Stock\n| year             = 2001\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=irNKAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9781579107963\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Edwards\n| first1           = James R.\n| title            = The Gospel According to Mark\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 2002\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=0MjWS_4La_EC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780851117782\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Getty-Sullivan\n| first1           = Mary Ann \n| title            = Parables of the Kingdom: Jesus and the Use of Parables in the Synoptic Tradition\n| publisher        = Liturgical Press\n| year             = 2007\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=zt3vK-hJzQYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780814629932\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Keener\n| first1           = Craig\n| title            = A Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 1999\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=sWzhEdBZOp4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=A+Commentary+on+the+Gospel+of+Matthew#v=onepage&q=fig%20tree&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780802838216\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Kinman\n| first1           = Brent\n| title            = Jesus' entry into Jerusalem: in the context of Lukan theology and the politics of his day\n| publisher        = Brill\n| year             = 1995\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=pRdiwjAeYLkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jesus%27+entry+into+Jerusalem:+in+the+context+of+Lukan+theology+and+the+politics+of+his+day#v=onepage&q=Jesus'%20entry%20into%20Jerusalem%3A%20in%20the%20context%20of%20Lukan%20theology%20and%20the%20politics%20of%20his%20day&f=false\n| isbn             = 9004103309\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Perkins\n| first1           = Pheme \n| title            = Introduction to the Synoptic Gospels\n| publisher        = Eerdmans \n| year             = 2009\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=lMUZhdgmOR8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Pheme+Perkins%22#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9780802865533\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n| last1            = Reddish\n| first1           = Mitchell G.\n| title            = An Introduction to The Gospels\n| publisher        = Abingdon Press\n| year             = 2011\n| url              = https://books.google.com/?id=hliGUOv18cQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| isbn             = 9781426750083\n| ref              = harv\n}}\n\n{{Jesus footer}}\n{{Miracles of Jesus|state=expanded}}\n[[Category:Curses]]\n[[Category:Miracles of Jesus]]\n[[Category:Ficus| ]]\n[[Category:Trees in Christianity]]\n", "name_user": "58.160.136.168", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cursing_the_fig_tree"}
{"title_page": "Charles Francis Walsh", "text_new": "{{for|the football coach|Chile Walsh}}\n\n[[File:Charles Francis Walsh circa 1910.jpg|thumb|Charles Francis Walsh in 1910]]\n'''Charles Francis Walsh''' (October 27, 1877 &ndash; October 3, 1912) was an American pioneer aviator who died in a crash in [[Trenton, New Jersey]].\n\n==Early life==\nCharles Francis Walsh was born in [[Mission Valley, California]], on October 27, 1877, to Mr. and Mrs. Walter C. Walsh. When he was a young boy, the family moved to nearby [[San Diego, California]]. Growing up, he worked in his father's grocery store.  Enterprising even at an early age, he started his own bicycle business as a teenager, but this would be the first of several unsuccessful ventures for Walsh until his early thirties.  In 1901, at the age of 24, he hitchhiked to Los Angeles and took a job as a [[stationary engineer]] at the California General Hospital in [[Los Angeles]]. It was there that he met a young nursing student named Alice Connolly.  They were married on September 23, 1903.\n\nIn January 1904, he and his new wife moved to [[Winslow, Arizona]], where he went to work for the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] as a freight train engineer.  Charles grew impatient during what turned out to be a long and frustrating apprenticeship, so he moved back to Los Angeles to work in an oil refinery as a field engineer.  It was not long, however, before they ventured to [[Goldfield, Nevada]], to seek their share of the gold fortune believed to be there.  At first, the Walshes were able to make decent money supporting the blossoming mining industry of the town.  The couple did return to Los Angeles in the spring of 1905 to give birth to their son Kenneth, while Charles briefly returned to work in the oil fields.  They returned to Goldfield a short time later.  Alice gave birth to a daughter (Juanita) there the following year.  When Goldfield died a quick death in 1907, however, a financially troubled Walsh was forced to move his family into his father's house at 17th and K streets in San Diego.\n\nCharles found work as an elevator operator in a local hotel.  Walsh became fascinated with aviation from reading about the subject in the local newspapers. Using only pictures from these newspapers, he sketched his own airplane design in between elevator trips at work and was determined to fly it one day.  In 1909, Walsh convinced a small group of local investors to open the first airplane manufacturing company in California.<ref name=Matt2000>Matt, P. R. (n.d.). Charles Francis Walsh (K. C. Rust, Ed.). Historical Aviation Album, IX.\nRetrieved from NASM Archives Technical Reference Files Walsh, Charles Frances, CW-103000-02</ref>\n\n==First airplane==\nThe San Diego Aeroplane Manufacturing Company incorporated on August 25, 1909, capitalized at $200,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Company Formed to Build Aeroplanes |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-08-26_7.pdf}}</ref> The company was located in room 432 of the [[Keating Building]] on the corner of Fifth and F Streets in downtown San Diego.  Walsh was vice president and general manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=The San Diego Aeroplane Manufacturing Company, Inc. |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-09-25_7.pdf}}</ref> He built his airplane in the old Rogers carriage shop on Third Street (between E and F Streets) near the company headquarters.<ref>{{cite web |title=On Exhibit |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-10-26_14.pdf}}</ref>  This location is now a parking garage for the [[Westfield Horton Plaza]].\n\nBy late November, Walsh had essentially completed his airplane.  Built from seasoned spruce and piano wire it measured 40 feet long with a 50-foot wingspan.  It was reported to be the largest monoplane in the world at the time.  Like the Wright Brothers design, a motor drove twin pusher propellers through a bicycle chain.  The propellers were seven feet long and made of Oregon pine with hickory hubs.  Like Curtiss, he used a tricycle type landing gear and ailerons vice the Wright's wing warping method for lateral control of his Bleriot-type monoplane.  His wings tapered from curved in the middle to flat ends.  The reason given for this is that the newspaper picture he used as his template for the design had the ends of the wings cutoff, so that is how he thought they looked.  Attached to these was his specially designed device to automatically provide lateral stability to his airplane.  This consisted of a fifteen-pound weight suspended from a five-foot rod which was connected to both wingtips.  As air flow acted on the wings, the weight would act as to raise on wingtip and lower the other, maintaining lateral stability without pilot input.  For control, Walsh designed a dual lever system, closely resembling that of the Wright Brothers.  One controlled the engine and one controlled the pitch. It was powered by a 30 H. P. Cameron automobile engine.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Inventor Will Fly Worlds Largest Monoplane |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-11-21_7.pdf}}</ref>\n\nWalsh tested his airplane at the [[Coronado Island]] Country Club racetrack during the last week of December.  He was one of three local San Diego aviators, including [[Waldo Waterman]], attempting to enter an airplane in the [[1910 Los Angeles International Air Meet at Dominguez Field]].  The airplane was damaged during ground runs at Coronado on December 29.<ref>{{cite web |title=Local Aviators Have Usual Trouble |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-12-31_6_(1).pdf}}</ref>  His wife Alice sold her jewelry so that he could attend the event as a spectator.  While there, he made the most of the opportunity to learn about airplane design from the most legendary pioneers in aviation.  When it was decided that San Diego would host its own air meet immediately following the one in Los Angeles, Walsh hurried home to incorporate what he learned into his own design as he rebuilt his airplane ahead of the event.<ref>Morehouse, H. E. (n.d.). Unpublished manuscript, Harold E. Morehouse Flying Pioneers Biographies collection, National Air and Space Museum Archives</ref>\n\nHe shortened his wingspan by approximately five feet, shortened the front elevator support assembly by ten feet, and added a \"horizontal plane\" over the rear rudder.  He also removed one of his rear rudders and abandoned his problematic chain-drive, dual-propeller configuration for a single-propeller, direct-drive system.  Walsh ordered a new six-foot propeller and intended to purchase one from [[Charles K. Hamilton]] upon his arrival at Coronado for the 1910 San Diego Aviation Meet.  All of this yielded a 100-pound savings in weight and better controllability.  His Cameron engine was raised two feet above the lower level of the main frame and produced 2000 rpm.<ref>{{cite web |title=$1000 Added to Aviation Prize |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:January_22_1910(Coronado).pdf}}</ref>\n\n===1910 San Diego Aviation Meet===\nDuring the [[1910 Los Angeles International Air Meet at Dominguez Field]], Charles K. Hamilton was invited by some San Diego businessmen to come to [[Coronado Island]] and attempt to beat the altitude record that [[Louis Paulhan]] set during that meet.  For the people of San Diego, the event was about attracting aviation to San Diego and raising money for the [[Panama-California Exposition]] the city planned to host in 1915.  [[Glenn Curtiss]] was in search of a suitable location for a winter headquarters and asked Hamilton to scout out San Diego for him.  He loaned Hamilton his [[Curtiss No. 2]] \"Reims Racer\" for this purpose.  The 1910 San Diego Aviation Meet was scheduled for January 23\u201325.  Charles F. Walsh was guaranteed the first $500 in profits to demonstrate his airplane on the opening day of the meet.<ref>Jackrabbits to jets: the history of Naval Air Station, North Island, San Diego, California Elretta Sudsbury - San Diego Pub. Co. - 1992</ref>  Walsh destroyed his airplane during his demonstration on the opening day of the meet when he was forced to taxi his airplane into a fence to avoid hitting Hamilton and the Reims Racer.  Two days later, Hamilton took Walsh along for a flight as a passenger in the Reims Racer.  This was the first flight for Walsh.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hamilton Wrecks Biplane in the Last Flight of Meet |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-01-26_6.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur aviation career==\n===Imperial Beach, California===\nFollowing the San Diego Aviation Meet, Walsh built a new airplane in less than 30 days.<ref name=SDUnionJune2>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Walsh_crash,_June_1910.pdf]</ref>  He was invited by a San Diego developer named E W Peterson to move his airplane to nearby Imperial Beach, California.  Peterson had three 30-foot-wide by 600-foot-long runways graded for this purpose.  Around April 1, 1910, Walsh began developing an aviation camp there while testing his new airplane.  The plane was a nearly exact copy of the Reims Racer in which he had flown as a passenger with Charles K. Hamilton.  Walsh added features of his own design that he hoped would simplify controllability, however.  Instead of a shoulder yoke for lateral control, Walsh mounted the steering wheel to a post on a double hinge, allowing for dual-axis control to operate the ailerons in addition to the elevators via a wire connection to the ailerons from the base of the control yoke. The engine-shutoff and starting wheel brake were controlled by a single lever fastened directly over the left side of the foot rest.  The same motion of the foot-operated both devices.  The engine speed lever was still connected to the frame next to the pilot.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roehrig Biplane Is Nearly Ready For Its First Tryout |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-04-08_19.pdf}}</ref>  A day or two later, Walsh added a thrust bearing to his engine, yielding an additional 25% increase in speed.  On April 10, 1910, approximately 100 onlookers witnessed his first flight.  Reaching an altitude of 15\u201320 feet, he flew for approximately 400 feet over the Imperial Beach runway before executing a reportedly flawless landing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh In His New Biplane Flies 400 feet on Beach |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-04-11_8.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy late May, he had already turned down offers to perform during the Fourth of July celebration of Baker City, Oregon; St. Louis, Missouri; and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.  The personal expense to him for such long distance trips made him concentrate on opportunities closer to San Diego.  He also made significant improvements to his airplane by this time, adding steel-rimmed wheels for his landing gear and installing a more advanced propeller.  To compensate for the aft center of gravity resulting from the increased weight of his engine relative to the one that powered the Reims Racer that he faithfully modeled his airplane after, he modified his tail to a box design, vice the single elevator.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Aviator Is Sought By Promoters of 3 Cities |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-05-25_5.pdf}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, Walsh suffered a major setback when his airplane crashed following a steep turn during a practice run on the aviation course.  It was quickly determined that his engine could not provide sufficient thrust to maintain altitude at steep angles of bank.  While this accident almost convinced Walsh to abandon aviation altogether, fellow Imperial Beach aviator B F Roehrig began an effort to raise money for a better engine.  He had made over 40 flights at this point. Most were straight and level below 50&nbsp;ft covering distances of 100 to 1000 feet as he gained confidence in himself and his airplane.<ref name=\"SDUnionJune2\" />  On the Fourth of July, he performed three aerial demonstrations at Imperial Beach before a crowd of 300\u2013400 curious onlookers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh Celebrates Fourth in Mid-Air |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-07-07_3.pdf}}</ref>  Later that month, Walsh acquired a more powerful 40&nbsp;hp Elbridge engine, which he rented from another San Diego aviation hopeful.  The more powerful engine quickly gave him the confidence to take his aviation to a larger venue.<ref>{{cite web |title=ED PICKELL OFFERS ENGINE |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh4.htm |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles===\nBy early September, 1910, Walsh was established at the [[Los Angeles Motordrome]], where the Aero Club of California had established an aviation camp.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"San Diego Aviator Tries For Honors.\" |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_Article_about_Walsh_moving_to_Los_Angeles_to_Take_Part_in_Novice_Air_Meet.pdf}}</ref>  Powered by his three-cylinder Elbridge featherweight, Walsh dominated a small field of fellow amateur Southern California aviators in the novice air meet held at the motordrome from 22\u201323 October, winning every event.  Prizes included cash and trophies, including the San Diego Cup for highest altitude.  The event also earned him notoriety.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crosse |first1=John |title=Playa del Rey: Speed Capital of the World, The Los(t) Angeles Motordrome, 1910\u20131913 |url=https://socalarchhistory.blogspot.com/2011/03/first-board-track-opened-at-los-angeles.html |website=Southern California Architectural History |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterward, Walsh became aligned with Macomber Aeroplane Engine Company, a local rotary engine manufacturer in Los Angeles, and replaced his Elbridge Featherweight with the first Macomber rotary engine ever built.  The engine did not perform well and prevented Walsh from participating in the second Los Angeles Air Meet at Dominguez Field in late December 1910.  On February 19, 1911, Walsh took his entire family flying, powered by an improved Macomber engine.  Charlie, Alice, Kenneth, and Juanita became the first family to every fly together in an airplane.  On March 4, 1911, [[Harry Harkness]] contracted Walsh to build an airplane for use by his chief mechanic John Kiley to learn to fly at the Harkness camp at North Island in San Diego, California.<ref>{{cite web |title=Harkness to Fly Biplane Built By San Diegan |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Macomber_(McComber)_Engine_and_Harry_Harkness_Purchases_Airpplane_From_Charlie_Walsh.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Harkness and Walsh Silver Darts===\nWalsh delivered the plane to John Kiley at the Harkness aviation camp at North Island on April 7, 1911.  According to at least one source, Walsh added \"silver dust\" to the unbleached muslin of the flying surfaces.  This earned the aircraft the name \"Silver Dart\".  Harkness paid Walsh $5000 for the plane, finally making him solvent.  A week later, Walsh crashed his plane at Dominguez Field while attempting to qualify as the Aero Club of California's first licensed aviator.  At some point, Walsh built a Silver Dart of his own.  There seems to be disagreement as the whether the Walsh Silver Dart was built before or after his crash at Dominguez.  Like the Silver Dart he sold to [[Harry Harkness]], his was based on the Curtiss airplane of the day, but with four Farman-type ailerons mounted flush to the end of all four wings replacing the Curtiss-style ailerons normally located between the upper and lower wing.  The upper and lower ailerons were connected to each other via a vertical pole and operated in unison.  They were moved via wires connected to the pilots steering wheel post.  The wings also had about 1/3 more surface area than a Curtiss, spanning 40 feet with a 4.5 foot chord.  It measured 37 feet from the tip of the forward elevator to the tail of the rudder.  Both the rudder and front elevator were double surfaced, or box-type, with the rudder being enclosed by a pair of two foot square vertical wings on either side of the horizontal surface.  There was no elevator function to the tail.  The tail and elevator surfaces measured approximately two feet by six feet and were set much farther out from the wings than a normal Curtiss.  Unlike the Harkness airplane, however, this Silver Dart was powered by the first production 40&nbsp;hp, four-cylinder Hall-Scott engine which turned an eight-foot propeller.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Aviator Falls 100 Feet In Biplane; Uninjured |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:April_14,_1911_Walsh_Fails_Pilots_License.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Macomber Rotary Aeroplane Motors |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh4.htm |website=Charles F. Walsh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh Makes Daring Flights |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Description_of_Harkness_Airplane_Built_by_Charles_F._Walsh.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition aviator==\n===Pacific Aviation Company===\nWalsh began his career as a professional exhibition aviator with the Pacific Aviation Company, owned by the Manning Brothers of Portland, Oregon.  His first event was May 11\u201312, 1911 in [[Roseburg, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Flies Here |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pacific_Aviation_Company,_1911.pdf}}</ref>  He kept a very busy schedule throughout the [[Pacific Northwest]] and endured some close calls and crashes.  At his event at Laramie, Wyoming, on July 31, he set a record for the highest elevation at which airplane flight was ever successfully conducted in the United States (7200 feet).   While Alice Walsh would later recall that Charles had his Silver Dart stolen at [[Kearney, Nebraska]], about a week later by the Manning Brothers, this account is disputed by local newspapers.  His airplane was reportedly almost completely destroyed when he hit a tree during his exhibition there on August 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=FRAGMENT FROM AERO |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh6.htm |website=earlyaviators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Smashes His Machine at Kearney |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Article_describing_how_aviator_Charles_F._Walsh_destroyed_his_airplane_at_Kearney,_NE.pdf}}</ref>\n\nFollowing that, on August 12, Charles Walsh landed in a cornfield while performing an exhibition at [[Fremont, Nebraska]].  The locals were very upset by what they considered a poor showing by Walsh.  The farmer who owned the field sued the Pacific Aviation Company a few days later for $100 in damages to his crops and a local judge confiscated the airplane pending a settlement.  This was perhaps the first such lawsuit of its kind.<ref>{{cite web |title=In Row Over Aero Flight |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Norfolk_weekly_news-journal_1911-08-18_9.pdf}}</ref>  On August 24, the Pacific Aviation Company settled a suit brought by the local aviation committee of Fremont for $300.  Walsh then sued the Pacific Aviation Company for $56.25 that he felt was owed to him as his share of ticket sales for the event.  This resulted in an [[attachment (law)]] being executed against the airplane.  Walsh and Manning then had an altercation in front of the Terry Hotel in Fremont that night over Manning deducting airplane repair costs from his share of ticket sales.  This was something Walsh claimed clearly violated his contract.  According to the local newspaper covering the event, Walsh did not own any interest in the plane.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Flies Here |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Walsh_Sues_Manager_Newspaper_Article.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Curtiss Exhibition Company===\n\nFollowing the [[1911 Chicago International Aviation Meet]], Walsh became a contract demonstration pilot with the Curtiss Exhibition Company.<ref>{{cite web |title=CURTISS EXHIBITION COMPANY |url=http://www.earlyaviators.com/ewalsh7.htm |website=earlyaviators.com}}</ref>  On August 31, 1911, he reportedly flew his newly assigned 75&nbsp;hp Curtiss pusher for the first time at [[Sterling, Illinois]], without incident, followed by an event in Iowa.<ref>Proves That Man Can At Last Fly Sterling Gazette, 31 Aug. 1911, pp. 1\u20135.</ref>  Walsh then returned to Nebraska, performing aerial demonstrations until the first week of October.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Birdman at the Fair |url=https://history.nebraska.gov/blog/birdman-fair |website=History Nebraska Blog |publisher=History Nebraska |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>      \nOn October 12, crowds gathered at Traction Park in Albuquerque, New Mexico, to watch Walsh become the first pilot to fly over the Rio Grande Valley.  The [[Albuquerque International Sunport]] has a 1914 Curtiss-style pusher representative of the one flown by Walsh on display in the terminal which helps commemorate the event.  He continued on a very busy schedule for the rest of the year.\n\nFor Walsh, 1912 began by making flights over [[Havana]], Cuba, on New Years Day.  His demonstration flights in that city included flying the first woman passenger in Cuba.  He spent the rest of January on a very busy tour throughout Texas. His flying soon became influenced by [[Lincoln Beachy]]. He crashed and died on October 3, 1912, in [[Trenton, New Jersey]], and was buried in [[Calvary Cemetery, San Diego]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Aviator Walsh |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w6deAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bFMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6382,1965077&dq=charles+walsh+aviator&hl=en |quote=Charles Walsh, the aviator, who appeared in Portsmouth last June and gave exhibition flights with his aeroplane, starting from the Portsmouth Driving park, was instantly killed last Thursday ... at Trenton, New Jersey ... |newspaper=[[Portsmouth Daily Times]] |date=October 4, 1912 |accessdate=2013-04-07 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*[http://www.earlyaviators.com/ewalsh.htm Charles Francis Walsh] at [[Early Aviators]]\n*[http://www.deford.com/walsh/ Image gallery]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Charles Francis}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:Aviators killed in aviation accidents or incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego County, California]]\n[[Category:People from Winslow, Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the football coach|Chile Walsh}}\n\n[[File:Charles Francis Walsh circa 1910.jpg|thumb|Charles Francis Walsh in 1910]]\n'''Charles Francis Walsh''' (October 27, 1877 &ndash; October 3, 1912) was an American pioneer aviator who died in a crash in [[Trenton, New Jersey]].\n\n==Early life==\nCharles Francis Walsh was born in [[Mission Valley, California]], on October 27, 1877, to Mr. and Mrs. Walter C. Walsh. When he was a young boy, the family moved to nearby [[San Diego, California]]. Growing up, he worked in his father's grocery store.  Enterprising even at an early age, he started his own bicycle business as a teenager, but this would be the first of several unsuccessful ventures for Walsh until his early thirties.  In 1901, at the age of 24, he hitchhiked to Los Angeles and took a job as a [[stationary engineer]] at the California General Hospital in [[Los Angeles]]. It was there that he met a young nursing student named Alice Connolly.  They were married on September 23, 1903.\n\nIn January 1904, he and his new wife moved to [[Winslow, Arizona]], where he went to work for the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] as a freight train engineer.  Charles grew impatient during what turned out to be a long and frustrating apprenticeship, so he moved back to Los Angeles to work in an oil refinery as a field engineer.  It was not long, however, before they ventured to [[Goldfield, Nevada]], to seek their share of the gold fortune believed to be there.  At first, the Walshes were able to make decent money supporting the blossoming mining industry of the town.  The couple did return to Los Angeles in the spring of 1905 to give birth to their son Kenneth, while Charles briefly returned to work in the oil fields.  They returned to Goldfield a short time later.  Alice gave birth to a daughter (Juanita) there the following year.  When Goldfield died a quick death in 1907, however, a financially troubled Walsh was forced to move his family into his father's house at 17th and K streets in San Diego.\n\nCharles found work as an elevator operator in a local hotel.  Walsh became fascinated with aviation from reading about the subject in the local newspapers. Using only pictures from these newspapers, he sketched his own airplane design in between elevator trips at work and was determined to fly it one day.  In 1909, Walsh convinced a small group of local investors to open the first airplane manufacturing company in California.<ref name=Matt2000>Matt, P. R. (n.d.). Charles Francis Walsh (K. C. Rust, Ed.). Historical Aviation Album, IX.\nRetrieved from NASM Archives Technical Reference Files Walsh, Charles Frances, CW-103000-02</ref>\n\n==First airplane==\nThe San Diego Aeroplane Manufacturing Company incorporated on August 25, 1909, capitalized at $200,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Company Formed to Build Aeroplanes |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-08-26_7.pdf}}</ref> The company was located in room 432 of the [[Keating Building]] on the corner of Fifth and F Streets in downtown San Diego.  Walsh was vice president and general manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=The San Diego Aeroplane Manufacturing Company, Inc. |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-09-25_7.pdf}}</ref> He built his airplane in the old Rogers carriage shop on Third Street (between E and F Streets) near the company headquarters.<ref>{{cite web |title=On Exhibit |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-10-26_14.pdf}}</ref>  This location is now a parking garage for the [[Westfield Horton Plaza]].\n\nBy late November, Walsh had essentially completed his airplane.  Built from seasoned spruce and piano wire it measured 40 feet long with a 50-foot wingspan.  It was reported to be the largest monoplane in the world at the time.  Like the Wright Brothers design, a motor drove twin pusher propellers through a bicycle chain.  The propellers were seven feet long and made of Oregon pine with hickory hubs.  Like Curtiss, he used a tricycle type landing gear and ailerons vice the Wright's wing warping method for lateral control of his Bleriot-type monoplane.  His wings tapered from curved in the middle to flat ends.  The reason given for this is that the newspaper picture he used as his template for the design had the ends of the wings cutoff, so that is how he thought they looked.  Attached to these was his specially designed device to automatically provide lateral stability to his airplane.  This consisted of a fifteen-pound weight suspended from a five-foot rod which was connected to both wingtips.  As air flow acted on the wings, the weight would act as to raise on wingtip and lower the other, maintaining lateral stability without pilot input.  For control, Walsh designed a dual lever system, closely resembling that of the Wright Brothers.  One controlled the engine and one controlled the pitch. It was powered by a 30 H. P. Cameron automobile engine.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Inventor Will Fly Worlds Largest Monoplane |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-11-21_7.pdf}}</ref>\n\nWalsh tested his airplane at the [[Coronado Island]] Country Club racetrack during the last week of December.  He was one of three local San Diego aviators, including [[Waldo Waterman]], attempting to enter an airplane in the [[1910 Los Angeles International Air Meet at Dominguez Field]].  The airplane was damaged during ground runs at Coronado on December 29.<ref>{{cite web |title=Local Aviators Have Usual Trouble |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1909-12-31_6_(1).pdf}}</ref>  His wife Alice sold her jewelry so that he could attend the event as a spectator.  While there, he made the most of the opportunity to learn about airplane design from the most legendary pioneers in aviation.  When it was decided that San Diego would host its own air meet immediately following the one in Los Angeles, Walsh hurried home to incorporate what he learned into his own design as he rebuilt his airplane ahead of the event.<ref>Morehouse, H. E. (n.d.). Unpublished manuscript, Harold E. Morehouse Flying Pioneers Biographies collection, National Air and Space Museum Archives</ref>\n\nHe shortened his wingspan by approximately five feet, shortened the front elevator support assembly by ten feet, and added a \"horizontal plane\" over the rear rudder.  He also removed one of his rear rudders and abandoned his problematic chain-drive, dual-propeller configuration for a single-propeller, direct-drive system.  Walsh ordered a new six-foot propeller and intended to purchase one from [[Charles K. Hamilton]] upon his arrival at Coronado for the 1910 San Diego Aviation Meet.  All of this yielded a 100-pound savings in weight and better controllability.  His Cameron engine was raised two feet above the lower level of the main frame and produced 2000 rpm.<ref>{{cite web |title=$1000 Added to Aviation Prize |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:January_22_1910(Coronado).pdf}}</ref>\n\n===1910 San Diego Aviation Meet===\nDuring the [[1910 Los Angeles International Air Meet at Dominguez Field]], Charles K. Hamilton was invited by some San Diego businessmen to come to [[Coronado Island]] and attempt to beat the altitude record that [[Louis Paulhan]] set during that meet.  For the people of San Diego, the event was about attracting aviation to San Diego and raising money for the [[Panama-California Exposition]] the city planned to host in 1915.  [[Glenn Curtiss]] was in search of a suitable location for a winter headquarters and asked Hamilton to scout out San Diego for him.  He loaned Hamilton his [[Curtiss No. 2]] \"Reims Racer\" for this purpose.  The 1910 San Diego Aviation Meet was scheduled for January 23\u201325.  Charles F. Walsh was guaranteed the first $500 in profits to demonstrate his airplane on the opening day of the meet.<ref>Jackrabbits to jets: the history of Naval Air Station, North Island, San Diego, California Elretta Sudsbury - San Diego Pub. Co. - 1992</ref>  Walsh destroyed his airplane during his demonstration on the opening day of the meet when he was forced to taxi his airplane into a fence to avoid hitting Hamilton and the Reims Racer.  Two days later, Hamilton took Walsh along for a flight as a passenger in the Reims Racer.  This was the first flight for Walsh.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hamilton Wrecks Biplane in the Last Flight of Meet |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-01-26_6.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur aviation career==\n===Imperial Beach, California===\nFollowing the San Diego Aviation Meet, Walsh built a new airplane in less than 30 days.<ref name=SDUnionJune2>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Walsh_crash,_June_1910.pdf]</ref>  He was invited by a San Diego developer named E W Peterson to move his airplane to nearby Imperial Beach, California.  Peterson had three 30-foot-wide by 600-foot-long runways graded for this purpose.  Around April 1, 1910, Walsh began developing an aviation camp there while testing his new airplane.  The plane was a nearly exact copy of the Reims Racer in which he had flown as a passenger with Charles K. Hamilton.  Walsh added features of his own design that he hoped would simplify controllability, however.  Instead of a shoulder yoke for lateral control, Walsh mounted the steering wheel to a post on a double hinge, allowing for dual-axis control to operate the ailerons in addition to the elevators via a wire connection to the ailerons from the base of the control yoke. The engine-shutoff and starting wheel brake were controlled by a single lever fastened directly over the left side of the foot rest.  The same motion of the foot-operated both devices.  The engine speed lever was still connected to the frame next to the pilot.<ref>{{cite web |title=Roehrig Biplane Is Nearly Ready For Its First Tryout |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-04-08_19.pdf}}</ref>  A day or two later, Walsh added a thrust bearing to his engine, yielding an additional 25% increase in speed.  On April 10, 1910, approximately 100 onlookers witnessed his first flight.  Reaching an altitude of 15\u201320 feet, he flew for approximately 400 feet over the Imperial Beach runway before executing a reportedly flawless landing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh In His New Biplane Flies 400 feet on Beach |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-04-11_8.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy late May, he had already turned down offers to perform during the Fourth of July celebration of Baker City, Oregon; St. Louis, Missouri; and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.  The personal expense to him for such long distance trips made him concentrate on opportunities closer to San Diego.  He also made significant improvements to his airplane by this time, adding steel-rimmed wheels for his landing gear and installing a more advanced propeller.  To compensate for the aft center of gravity resulting from the increased weight of his engine relative to the one that powered the Reims Racer that he faithfully modeled his airplane after, he modified his tail to a box design, vice the single elevator.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Aviator Is Sought By Promoters of 3 Cities |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-05-25_5.pdf}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, Walsh suffered a major setback when his airplane crashed following a steep turn during a practice run on the aviation course.  It was quickly determined that his engine could not provide sufficient thrust to maintain altitude at steep angles of bank.  While this accident almost convinced Walsh to abandon aviation altogether, fellow Imperial Beach aviator B F Roehrig began an effort to raise money for a better engine.  He had made over 40 flights at this point. Most were straight and level below 50&nbsp;ft covering distances of 100 to 1000 feet as he gained confidence in himself and his airplane.<ref name=\"SDUnionJune2\" />  On the Fourth of July, he performed three aerial demonstrations at Imperial Beach before a crowd of 300\u2013400 curious onlookers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh Celebrates Fourth in Mid-Air |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_1910-07-07_3.pdf}}</ref>  Later that month, Walsh acquired a more powerful 40&nbsp;hp Elbridge engine, which he rented from another San Diego aviation hopeful.  The more powerful engine quickly gave him the confidence to take his aviation to a larger venue.<ref>{{cite web |title=ED PICKELL OFFERS ENGINE |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh4.htm |accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles===\nBy early September, 1910, Walsh was established at the [[Los Angeles Motordrome]], where the Aero Club of California had established an aviation camp.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"San Diego Aviator Tries For Honors.\" |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:San_Diego_Union_Article_about_Walsh_moving_to_Los_Angeles_to_Take_Part_in_Novice_Air_Meet.pdf}}</ref>  Powered by his three-cylinder Elbridge featherweight, Walsh dominated a small field of fellow amateur Southern California aviators in the novice air meet held at the motordrome from 22\u201323 October, winning every event.  Prizes included cash and trophies, including the San Diego Cup for highest altitude.  The event also earned him notoriety.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crosse |first1=John |title=Playa del Rey: Speed Capital of the World, The Los(t) Angeles Motordrome, 1910\u20131913 |url=https://socalarchhistory.blogspot.com/2011/03/first-board-track-opened-at-los-angeles.html |website=Southern California Architectural History |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterward, Walsh became aligned with Macomber Aeroplane Engine Company, a local rotary engine manufacturer in Los Angeles, and replaced his Elbridge Featherweight with the first Macomber rotary engine ever built.  The engine did not perform well and prevented Walsh from participating in the second Los Angeles Air Meet at Dominguez Field in late December 1910.  On February 19, 1911, Walsh took his entire family flying, powered by an improved Macomber engine.  Charlie, Alice, Kenneth, and Juanita became the first family to every fly together in an airplane.  On March 4, 1911, [[Harry Harkness]] contracted Walsh to build an airplane for use by his chief mechanic John Kiley to learn to fly at the Harkness camp at North Island in San Diego, California.<ref>{{cite web |title=Harkness to Fly Biplane Built By San Diegan |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Macomber_(McComber)_Engine_and_Harry_Harkness_Purchases_Airpplane_From_Charlie_Walsh.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Harkness and Walsh Silver Darts===\nWalsh delivered the plane to John Kiley at the Harkness aviation camp at North Island on April 7, 1911.  According to at least one source, Walsh added \"silver dust\" to the unbleached muslin of the flying surfaces.  This earned the aircraft the name \"Silver Dart\".  Harkness paid Walsh $5000 for the plane, finally making him solvent.  A week later, Walsh crashed his plane at Dominguez Field while attempting to qualify as the Aero Club of California's first licensed aviator.  At some point, Walsh built a Silver Dart of his own.  There seems to be disagreement as the whether the Walsh Silver Dart was built before or after his crash at Dominguez.  Like the Silver Dart he sold to [[Harry Harkness]], his was based on the Curtiss airplane of the day, but with four Farman-type ailerons mounted flush to the end of all four wings replacing the Curtiss-style ailerons normally located between the upper and lower wing.  The upper and lower ailerons were connected to each other via a vertical pole and operated in unison.  They were moved via wires connected to the pilots steering wheel post.  The wings also had about 1/3 more surface area than a Curtiss, spanning 40 feet with a 4.5 foot chord.  It measured 37 feet from the tip of the forward elevator to the tail of the rudder.  Both the rudder and front elevator were double surfaced, or box-type, with the rudder being enclosed by a pair of two foot square vertical wings on either side of the horizontal surface.  There was no elevator function to the tail.  The tail and elevator surfaces measured approximately two feet by six feet and were set much farther out from the wings than a normal Curtiss.  Unlike the Harkness airplane, however, this Silver Dart was powered by the first production 40&nbsp;hp, four-cylinder Hall-Scott engine which turned an eight-foot propeller.<ref>{{cite web |title=San Diego Aviator Falls 100 Feet In Biplane; Uninjured |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:April_14,_1911_Walsh_Fails_Pilots_License.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Macomber Rotary Aeroplane Motors |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh4.htm |website=Charles F. Walsh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Walsh Makes Daring Flights |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Description_of_Harkness_Airplane_Built_by_Charles_F._Walsh.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition aviator==\n===Pacific Aviation Company===\nWalsh began his career as a professional exhibition aviator with the Pacific Aviation Company, owned by the Manning Brothers of Portland, Oregon.  His first event was May 11\u201312, 1911 in [[Roseburg, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Flies Here |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pacific_Aviation_Company,_1911.pdf}}</ref>  He kept a very busy schedule throughout the [[Pacific Northwest]] and endured some close calls and crashes.  At his event at Laramie, Wyoming, on July 31, he set a record for the highest elevation at which airplane flight was ever successfully conducted in the United States (7200 feet).   While Alice Walsh would later recall that Charles had his Silver Dart stolen at [[Kearney, Nebraska]], about a week later by the Manning Brothers, this account is disputed by local newspapers.  His airplane was reportedly almost completely destroyed when he hit a tree during his exhibition there on August 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=FRAGMENT FROM AERO |url=http://earlyaviators.com/ewalsh6.htm |website=earlyaviators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Smashes His Machine at Kearney |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Article_describing_how_aviator_Charles_F._Walsh_destroyed_his_airplane_at_Kearney,_NE.pdf}}</ref>\n\nFollowing that, on August 12, Charles Walsh landed in a cornfield while performing an exhibition at [[Fremont, Nebraska]].  The locals were very upset by what they considered a poor showing by Walsh.  The farmer who owned the field sued the Pacific Aviation Company a few days later for $100 in damages to his crops and a local judge confiscated the airplane pending a settlement.  This was perhaps the first such lawsuit of its kind.<ref>{{cite web |title=In Row Over Aero Flight |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Norfolk_weekly_news-journal_1911-08-18_9.pdf}}</ref>  On August 24, the Pacific Aviation Company settled a suit brought by the local aviation committee of Fremont for $300.  Walsh then sued the Pacific Aviation Company for $56.25 that he felt was owed to him as his share of ticket sales for the event.  This resulted in an [[attachment (law)]] being executed against the airplane.  Walsh and Manning then had an altercation in front of the Terry Hotel in Fremont that night over Manning deducting airplane repair costs from his share of ticket sales.  This was something Walsh claimed clearly violated his contract.  According to the local newspaper covering the event, Walsh did not own any interest in the plane.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aviator Flies Here |url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Walsh_Sues_Manager_Newspaper_Article.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Curtiss Exhibition Company===\n\nFollowing the [[1911 Chicago International Aviation Meet]], Walsh became a contract demonstration pilot with the Curtiss Exhibition Company.<ref>{{cite web |title=CURTISS EXHIBITION COMPANY |url=http://www.earlyaviators.com/ewalsh7.htm |website=earlyaviators.com}}</ref>  On August 31, 1911, he reportedly flew his newly assigned 75&nbsp;hp Curtiss pusher for the first time at [[Sterling, Illinois]], without incident, followed by an event in Iowa.<ref>Proves That Man Can At Last Fly Sterling Gazette, 31 Aug. 1911, pp. 1\u20135.</ref>  Walsh then returned to Nebraska, performing aerial demonstrations until the first week of October.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Birdman at the Fair |url=https://history.nebraska.gov/blog/birdman-fair |website=History Nebraska Blog |publisher=History Nebraska |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>      \nOn October 12, crowds gathered at Traction Park in Albuquerque, New Mexico, to watch Walsh become the first pilot to fly over the Rio Grande Valley.  The [[Albuquerque International Sunport]] has a 1914 Curtiss-style pusher representative of the one flown by Walsh on display in the terminal which helps commemorate the event.  He continued on a very busy schedule for the rest of the year.\n\nFor Walsh, 1912 began by making flights over [[Havana]], Cuba, on New Years Day.  His demonstration flights in that city included flying the first woman passenger in Cuba.  He spent the rest of January on a very busy tour throughout Texas. His flying soon became influenced by [[Lincoln Beachy]]. He crashed and died on October 3, 1912, in [[Trenton, New Jersey]], and was buried in [[Calvary Cemetery, San Diego]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Aviator Walsh |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w6deAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bFMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6382,1965077&dq=charles+walsh+aviator&hl=en |quote=Charles Walsh, the aviator, who appeared in Portsmouth last June and gave exhibition flights with his aeroplane, starting from the Portsmouth Driving park, was instantly killed last Thursday ... at Trenton, New Jersey ... |newspaper=[[Portsmouth Daily Times]] |date=October 4, 1912 |accessdate=2013-04-07 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*[http://www.earlyaviators.com/ewalsh.htm Charles Francis Walsh] at [[Early Aviators]]\n*[http://www.deford.com/walsh/ Image gallery]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Charles Francis}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego County, California]]\n[[Category:People from Winslow, Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Gildir", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:: +Category:Aviators killed in aviation accidents or incidents in the United States", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Francis_Walsh"}
{"title_page": "Rohit Shukla", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major]]\n| name          = Rohit Shukla\n| honorific_suffix = [[Shaurya Chakra|SC]], [[Sena Medal|SM]]\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = \n| death_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]\n| caste         = \n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|India}}\n| branch        = [[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[File:Major of the Indian Army.svg|24px]] [[Major]]\n| unit          = 44 Rashtriya Rifles\n| commands      = \n| battles       = \n| awards        = [[File:Shaurya Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]][[Shaurya Chakra]]<br>[[File:Sena Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Sena Medal]]\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n[[Major]] '''Rohit Shukla''' [[Shaurya Chakra|SC]], [[Sena Medal|SM]], is an [[Indian Army]] Officer of  [[Rashtriya Rifles|44 Rashtriya Rifles]]. He received the [[Shaurya Chakra]], the third highest peacetime military award from the [[President of India]], [[Ram Nath Kovind]] at the Defence Investiture Ceremony\u2013I, at a ceremony in [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]], [[New Delhi]] on March 27, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Major martyred in J&K gets gallantry award|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/major-martyred-jk-gets-gallantry-award/|publisher=[[Daily Excelsior]]|date=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kirti Chakra & Shaurya Chakra|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=175891|agency=[[Ministry of Defence]]|publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]]|date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> He is currently posted with the 44 Rashtriya Rifles in [[Pulwama]]'s Shadimarg area in [[Jammu & Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The man behind Tiger's hunt: Major Rohit Shukla|url=http://www.eenaduindia.com/news/national-news/2018/05/01181423/The-man-behind-the-Tigers-hunt-Major-Rohit-Shukla.vpf|publisher=eenaduindia|date=May 1, 2018}}</ref> Major Shukla was awarded the [[Sena Medal]] on January 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=411 Republic Day Gallantry and Other Defence Decorations Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=187777 |publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]] |date=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0907\u0938 \u091c\u093e\u0902\u092c\u093e\u091c \u0928\u0947 \u091a\u0941\u0928\u094c\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u0947\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0906\u0924\u0902\u0915\u0940 \u0915\u094b \u0909\u0924\u093e\u0930\u093e \u0925\u093e \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0918\u093e\u091f, \u0938\u0947\u0928\u093e \u092e\u0947\u0921\u0932 \u0938\u0947 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0928\u093f\u0924 |url=https://www.jagran.com/uttarakhand/dehradun-city-major-shukla-gets-sena-medal-18894186.html |publisher=[[Dainik Jagaran]] |date=January 28, 2019 |language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nShukla is an alumnus of [[St Joseph's Academy, Dehradun|St. Joseph Academy]]. He got into [[Indian Army]] by getting selected through [[National Defence Academy (India)|NDA]] examination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Family proud of Maj Shukla\u2019s heroics|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/uttarakhand/family-proud-of-maj-shukla-s-heroics/583761.html|publisher=[[Tribune India]]|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\nOn April 30, 2018, Major Shukla killed the category A++ terrorist of [[Hizbul Mujahideen]], Sameer Tiger in  a joint operation by  [[Jammu and Kashmir Police]], [[Indian Army]] and [[Central Reserve Police Force]]. A day before his encounter, Tiger threatened [[Indian Army]], specifically Major Shukla in a viral video.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Army Major Rohit Shukla killed Hizbul Mujahideen terrorist \u2018Tiger\u2019 in J&K's Pulwama|url=http://zeenews.india.com/jammu-and-kashmir/pulwama-encounter-how-army-major-killed-hizbul-mujahideen-terrorist-tiger-2104161.html|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=Apr 30, 2018}}</ref> Shukla was injured with a bullet wound on his right hand during the encounter and was undergoing treatment as of May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hassan|first1=Ishfaq-ul-|title=J&K gun battle: Sameer Tiger had dared Major Rohit Shukla 24 hours before death|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jk-gun-battle-sameer-tiger-had-dared-major-rohit-shukla-24-hours-before-death-2610607|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hussain|first1=Khalid|title=Army Major who killed Hizbul terrorist Sameer Tiger currently battling for life|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-army-major-who-killed-hizbul-terrorist-sameer-tiger-currently-battling-for-life-2610245|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=Apr 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BulletWound\">{{cite news |title=Family proud of Maj Shukla\u2019s heroics |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/uttarakhand/family-proud-of-maj-shukla-s-heroics/583761.html |accessdate=15 September 2018 |publisher=Tribune India |date=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nMajor Rohit Shukla has commanded more than 52 operations carried out by the [[Indian Army]] against terrorists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goel|first1=Pallavi|title=You\u2019ll Be Proud To Know What This Indian Army Officer Has Done For The Country!|url=https://topyaps.com/indian-army-officer|publisher=Topyaps.com|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the incident a rifleman, named Aurangzeb, who served with Shukla, was kidnapped, tortured, and killed, by opposition fighters.<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03/><ref name=news18-2019-07-23/>  They subsequently released gruesome video from his torture, on [[twitter]].  In Shukla's unit every soldier was paired with a partner, or buddy, with each member of the pair watching out for the other.  Aurangzeb had had been paired with Shukla on the mission where he killed Tiger, and this was the reason he was singled out for retaliation.  According to the ''[[India Times]]'' their video specifically shows Aurangzeb being tortured into admitting he was Shukla's buddy.\n\n''India Times'' speculated that the release of this video might trigger India's [[News Broadcasting Standards Authority]] to step in to try to control the rebroadcasting of video and audio from opposition elements.<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03/>  The Army had explicitly called on news agencies to refrain from rebroadcasting the video of Shukla's partner's torture and killing, and several agencies rebroadcast it anyhow.\n\nThe Army conducted an inquiry, after the video was released, as the identity of the buddies is classified, and the video suggested there had been a breach of security.<ref name=theprint2019-02-07/>  \n\nOn February 6, 2019, [[Mehbooba Mufti]], a former [[Chief Minister of Jammu and Kashmir]], criticized Shukla over his treatment of a civilian captive.<ref name=timesnownews2019-02-06/>  She told reporters she had recently visited a youth, in hospital, following interrogation by Shukla.  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/news-channels-may-have-to-get-approval-for-telecasting-material-issued-by-terrorist-organisations/articleshow/69166838.cms\n| title       = News channels may have to get approval for telecasting material issued by terrorist organisations\n| work        = [[India Times]]\n| author      = Shaurya Karanbir Gurung\n| date        = 2019-05-03\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = <!-- Aurangzeb, who was serving with the army\u2019s 44 Rashtriya Rifles in Jammu and Kashmir, was heading to his home to celebrate Eid when he was abducted by terrorists on June 14. Hours later his bullet ridden body was found in Gussu village, Pulwama. --> In a video released on social-media site, Twitter, he is seen being interrogated by his captors about his closeness to Major Rohit Shukla, who had gunned down a Hizbul Mujahideen commander named Sameer Tiger in Kashmir in April last year. Aurangzeb had confirmed that he was Shukla\u2019s \u2018buddy\u2019 (army\u2019s buddy system in which two soldiers are paired together).\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=news18-2019-07-23>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.news18.com/news/india/brothers-of-slain-rifleman-aurangzeb-join-indian-army-to-keep-legacy-alive-2242073.html\n| title       = Brothers of Rifleman Aurangzeb, Abducted and Killed by Militants, Join Indian Army to Keep Legacy Alive\n| work        = [[CNN-News18]]\n| author      = Mufti Islah\n| date        = 2019-07-23\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live      \n| quote       = Aurangzeb, who was part of the South Kashmir based 44 Battalion Rashtriya Rifles, was waylaid by militants and subsequently killed few kilometres away from his residence. <!-- His bullet-riddled body was found at a village in Pulwama, hours after he had left his unit in Shopian to join his family in Rajouri for Eid celebrations. He was part of Major Rohit Shukla's team that gunned down Hizbul Mujahideen terrorist Sameer Tiger. -->\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=theprint2019-02-07>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://theprint.in/defence/indian-army-probing-two-soldiers-for-tipping-off-militants-who-killed-rifleman-aurangzeb/189107/\n| title       = Indian Army probing two soldiers for \u2018tipping off\u2019 militants who killed rifleman Aurangzeb\n| work        = [[ThePrint]]\n| author      = Snehesh Alex Philip\n| date        = 2019-02-07\n| page        = \n| location    = \n| isbn        = \n| language    = \n| trans-title = \n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = Surprisingly, the militants seemed to know he was Major Shukla\u2019s \u201cbuddy\u201d, which is information of a highly classified nature.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=timesnownews2019-02-06>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/former-jammu-and-kashmir-cm-mehbooba-mufti-insults-indias-brave-remains-silent-over-terrorist-attacks/360688\n| title       = Former Jammu and Kashmir CM Mehbooba Mufti 'insults' India's brave, remains silent over terrorist attacks\n| work        = [[Times Now News]]\n| date        = 2019-02-06\n| page        = \n| location    = [[Pulwama]]\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = Former Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister and PDP leader Mehbooba Mufti, on Wednesday 'insulted' celebrated Indian Army officer Major Rohit Shukla saying that the officer 'tortured' a J&K youth while probing a matter- Times Now channel reported. \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Oj6lI7NG2uM CAUGHT ON CAMERA: When Major Rohit Shukla KILLING Sameer Tiger] on [[ABP News]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJzn74MmIcY Captain Rohit Shukla Shaurya Chakra \u2013 2018]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shukla, Rohit}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Shaurya Chakra]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sena Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Indian military awards and decorations]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix= [[Major]]\n|name=Rohit Shukla\n|honorific_suffix=[[Shaurya Chakra|SC]], [[Sena Medal|SM]]\n|image     = \n|caption   = \n|birth_date=\n|death_date=\n|birth_place= [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[India]]\n|caste= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flag|India}}\n|branch=[[Indian Army]]\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Major]]\n|unit= 44 Rashtriya Rifles\n|commands=\n|battles=\n|awards= [[File:Shaurya Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]][[Shaurya Chakra]]<br>[[File:Sena Medal 2.jpg|25px]] [[Sena Medal]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n[[Major]] '''Rohit Shukla''' [[Shaurya Chakra|SC]], [[Sena Medal|SM]], is an [[Indian Army]] Officer of  [[Rashtriya Rifles|44 Rashtriya Rifles]]. He received the [[Shaurya Chakra]], the third highest peacetime military award from the [[President of India]], [[Ram Nath Kovind]] at the Defence Investiture Ceremony\u2013I, at a ceremony in [[Rashtrapati Bhavan]], [[New Delhi]] on March 27, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Major martyred in J&K gets gallantry award|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/major-martyred-jk-gets-gallantry-award/|publisher=[[Daily Excelsior]]|date=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kirti Chakra & Shaurya Chakra|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=175891|agency=[[Ministry of Defence]]|publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]]|date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> He is currently posted with the 44 Rashtriya Rifles in [[Pulwama]]'s Shadimarg area in [[Jammu & Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The man behind Tiger's hunt: Major Rohit Shukla|url=http://www.eenaduindia.com/news/national-news/2018/05/01181423/The-man-behind-the-Tigers-hunt-Major-Rohit-Shukla.vpf|publisher=eenaduindia|date=May 1, 2018}}</ref> Major Shukla was awarded the [[Sena Medal]] on January 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=411 Republic Day Gallantry and Other Defence Decorations Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=187777 |publisher=[[Press Information Bureau]] |date=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0907\u0938 \u091c\u093e\u0902\u092c\u093e\u091c \u0928\u0947 \u091a\u0941\u0928\u094c\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u0947\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0906\u0924\u0902\u0915\u0940 \u0915\u094b \u0909\u0924\u093e\u0930\u093e \u0925\u093e \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0918\u093e\u091f, \u0938\u0947\u0928\u093e \u092e\u0947\u0921\u0932 \u0938\u0947 \u0938\u092e\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0928\u093f\u0924 |url=https://www.jagran.com/uttarakhand/dehradun-city-major-shukla-gets-sena-medal-18894186.html |publisher=[[Dainik Jagaran]] |date=January 28, 2019 |language=Hindi}}</ref>\n\nShukla is an alumnus of [[St Joseph's Academy, Dehradun|St. Joseph Academy]]. He got into [[Indian Army]] by getting selected through [[National Defence Academy (India)|NDA]] examination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Family proud of Maj Shukla\u2019s heroics|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/uttarakhand/family-proud-of-maj-shukla-s-heroics/583761.html|publisher=[[Tribune India]]|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2018, Major Shukla killed the category A++ terrorist of [[Hizbul Mujahideen]], Sameer Tiger in  a joint operation by  [[Jammu and Kashmir Police]], [[Indian Army]] and [[Central Reserve Police Force]]. A day before his encounter, Tiger threatened [[Indian Army]], specifically Major Shukla in a viral video.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Army Major Rohit Shukla killed Hizbul Mujahideen terrorist \u2018Tiger\u2019 in J&K's Pulwama|url=http://zeenews.india.com/jammu-and-kashmir/pulwama-encounter-how-army-major-killed-hizbul-mujahideen-terrorist-tiger-2104161.html|publisher=[[Zee News]]|date=Apr 30, 2018}}</ref> Shukla was injured with a bullet wound on his right hand during the encounter and was undergoing treatment as of May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hassan|first1=Ishfaq-ul-|title=J&K gun battle: Sameer Tiger had dared Major Rohit Shukla 24 hours before death|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jk-gun-battle-sameer-tiger-had-dared-major-rohit-shukla-24-hours-before-death-2610607|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hussain|first1=Khalid|title=Army Major who killed Hizbul terrorist Sameer Tiger currently battling for life|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-army-major-who-killed-hizbul-terrorist-sameer-tiger-currently-battling-for-life-2610245|publisher=[[DNA India]]|date=Apr 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BulletWound\">{{cite news |title=Family proud of Maj Shukla\u2019s heroics |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/uttarakhand/family-proud-of-maj-shukla-s-heroics/583761.html |accessdate=15 September 2018 |publisher=Tribune India |date=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nMajor Rohit Shukla has commanded more than 52 operations carried out by the [[Indian Army]] against terrorists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goel|first1=Pallavi|title=You\u2019ll Be Proud To Know What This Indian Army Officer Has Done For The Country!|url=https://topyaps.com/indian-army-officer|publisher=Topyaps.com|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the incident a rifleman, named Aurangzeb, who served with Shukla, was kidnapped, tortured, and killed, by opposition fighters.<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03/><ref name=news18-2019-07-23/>  They subsequently released gruesome video from his torture, on [[twitter]].  In Shukla's unit every soldier was paired with a partner, or buddy, with each member of the pair watching out for the other.  Aurangzeb had had been paired with Shukla on the mission where he killed Tiger, and this was the reason he was singled out for retaliation.  According to the ''[[India Times]]'' their video specifically shows Aurangzeb being tortured into admitting he was Shukla's buddy.\n\n''India Times'' speculated that the release of this video might trigger India's [[News Broadcasting Standards Authority]] to step in to try to control the rebroadcasting of video and audio from opposition elements.<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03/>  The Army had explicitly called on news agencies to refrain from rebroadcasting the video of Shukla's partner's torture and killing, and several agencies rebroadcast it anyhow.\n\nThe Army conducted an inquiry, after the video was released, as the identity of the buddies is classified, and the video suggested there had been a breach of security.<ref name=theprint2019-02-07/>  \n\nOn February 6, 2019, [[Mehbooba Mufti]], a former [[Chief Minister of Jammu and Kashmir]], criticized Shukla over his treatment of a civilian captive.<ref name=timesnownews2019-02-06/>  She told reporters she had recently visited a youth, in hospital, following interrogation by Shukla.  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=indiatimes2019-05-03>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/news-channels-may-have-to-get-approval-for-telecasting-material-issued-by-terrorist-organisations/articleshow/69166838.cms\n| title       = News channels may have to get approval for telecasting material issued by terrorist organisations\n| work        = [[India Times]]\n| author      = Shaurya Karanbir Gurung\n| date        = 2019-05-03\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = <!-- Aurangzeb, who was serving with the army\u2019s 44 Rashtriya Rifles in Jammu and Kashmir, was heading to his home to celebrate Eid when he was abducted by terrorists on June 14. Hours later his bullet ridden body was found in Gussu village, Pulwama. --> In a video released on social-media site, Twitter, he is seen being interrogated by his captors about his closeness to Major Rohit Shukla, who had gunned down a Hizbul Mujahideen commander named Sameer Tiger in Kashmir in April last year. Aurangzeb had confirmed that he was Shukla\u2019s \u2018buddy\u2019 (army\u2019s buddy system in which two soldiers are paired together).\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=news18-2019-07-23>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.news18.com/news/india/brothers-of-slain-rifleman-aurangzeb-join-indian-army-to-keep-legacy-alive-2242073.html\n| title       = Brothers of Rifleman Aurangzeb, Abducted and Killed by Militants, Join Indian Army to Keep Legacy Alive\n| work        = [[CNN-News18]]\n| author      = Mufti Islah\n| date        = 2019-07-23\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-09\n| url-status  = live      \n| quote       = Aurangzeb, who was part of the South Kashmir based 44 Battalion Rashtriya Rifles, was waylaid by militants and subsequently killed few kilometres away from his residence. <!-- His bullet-riddled body was found at a village in Pulwama, hours after he had left his unit in Shopian to 